me from any of several places called Bowley such as Bowley in Cadbury (Devon), a lost place called Bowley in Hailsham (Sussex), or Bowley in Blakemere (Herefordshire). The first is from Old English <i>boga</i> ‘bow, river bend’ + <i>lēah</i>. The second is from the Old English personal name <i>Buga</i> + + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. The third is named with Old English <i>bula</i> ‘bull’, perhaps a byname (see   Bull  ) + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’."]},{"name":"Buls","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Hyman, Hymie.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): unexplained. In Austrian Galicia the name was spelled <b>Bulz</b>.","North German: presumably a variant of   Bull   2."]},{"name":"Bulls","meanings":["Altered form of   Bull  , a surname of English or German origin, with the addition of excrescent <i>-s</i>.","In some cases possibly also an Americanized form of North German or Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic)   Buls  ."]}]},{"name":"Jed","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a short form of the biblical name  <b>Jedidiah</b> , now generally used as an independent given name. <i>Jedidiah</i> means ‘beloved of God’ in Hebrew, and was used as an alternative name of King Solomon (2 Samuel 12:25). It was a favourite with the Puritans, who considered themselves, too, to be loved by God, but the full form fell out of favour along with other rare or unwieldy Old Testament names.  See also  Ged ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355923,"age":11,"year":"1167","julianDay":2147298,"description":"Arrival of Normans at Baginbun in Co. Wexford thus started 800 year struggle between English and Irish.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Jed BULL was born in 1156, in Bridge End, County Donegal, Ireland. He had at least 1 daughter with Mary."},"et":{"1156–":"1156–Surnud","1157–Female":"1157–Surnud","1215–1249":"1215–1249","1156–Male":"1156–Surnud","1249":"1249","1